📘 03 — Password Hash Synchronization (PHS)
Medium‑depth explanation with Mahabharata‑aligned storytelling — GitBook Ready.

🏹 **Mahabharata Analogy —
“Sharing the encrypted royal seal, not the king’s secret mantra.”**
In ancient times:

Every king had a secret mantra used during rituals — known only to the royal priest.
But to allow allied kingdoms to verify the king’s authority, a royal seal was shared.
This seal:

proved legitimacy,
could not be reverse‑engineered into the secret mantra,
enabled secure recognition across kingdoms.



Password Hash Synchronization (PHS) works exactly the same way:

The secret password (mantra) stays safe in your on‑prem AD.
Only a double‑hashed, non‑reversible version (royal seal) is synced to Entra ID.

Thus, the cloud identifies the user securely — without ever learning the real password.

🔐 1. What Is Password Hash Synchronization? (Simple Definition)
Password Hash Synchronization (PHS) is a hybrid identity method where:

On‑premises Active Directory password hashes are
re‑hashed using SHA‑256 and
synced securely to Microsoft Entra ID.
Users authenticate directly with Entra ID (cloud authentication).
No password validation happens against on‑prem AD at sign‑in.

PHS is:

the simplest,
most reliable,
most recommended
method for cloud sign‑in.


🧠 2. How PHS Works (Medium‑Depth)
Here is the step‑by‑step breakdown:

⭐ Step 1 — User password exists in AD
Stored as an NT hash (never the plain password).

⭐ Step 2 — Azure AD Connect reads the password hash
But never the password.

⭐ Step 3 — AD hash is re‑hashed using SHA‑256
This creates a new irreversible hash specifically for Entra ID.

⭐ Step 4 — Rehashed value is sent to Entra ID
Using secure TLS channels.

⭐ Step 5 — Cloud authentication happens
User enters password on Microsoft login page.
Entra ID hashes it using the same operations and compares with the stored cloud hash.
If equal → authentication successful.

